body:
Can you attach an example that shows the issue?
```systemverilog
module process_test;
class A;
    local process proc2;
    task run;
        process proc1;
        proc1 = process::self();
        if (proc1 == proc2) begin
            $display("process is equal %p %p", proc1, proc2);
        end
        else begin
            $display("process is not equal %p %p", proc1, proc2);
            proc2 = proc1;
        end
    endtask

endclass
    initial begin
        A a;
        a = new();
        a.run();
        a.run();
    end
endmodule

```
During simulation, when invoking a.run() for the second time, the comparison between proc1 and proc2 unexpectedly returns "not equal". According to the code logic, proc2 should hold the value of proc1 from the first call, leading to an equality in the second comparison. However, the actual output shows they remain unequal:
```
process is not equal '{m_process:process} null
process is not equal '{m_process:process} '{m_process:process}
```
What 'verilator' command line do we use to run your example?
```bash
$VERILATOR_ROOT/bin/verilator  --binary -top sema_test sema_test.sv;./obj_dir/Vsema_test
```

What 'verilator --version' are you using?  Did you try it with the git master version?
```
rev v5.034-81-g464e19caa
```
What OS and distribution are you using?

Macos Sequoia 15.3.2

